segments.text: First of all, Mr. Heller, tell us something about your early life, including the names of your parents, the dates and places of their birth and death, the date and place of your birth, and the schools you attended before you entered Texas A&M.
Well, my father's name was Louis F. Heller.
I don't remember his date, but he was 49 years old when he died in 1940.
My mother's name was Annie Ann Haller.
She was 70 years old when she died in 1940.
I lived in Victoria and tended
St. Joseph's school, a Catholic school, before I went to A&M.
I don't know.
Do you remember where your mother and father were born?
My father was born in Victoria, Texas, and my mother in St. Louis, Missouri.
And she would have moved to Victoria?
Yeah, they come in there.

grandfather was a brewer and he put up a brewery down there in Victoria, Texas and was in business there up until the time they began to ship ice in there over the railroads and then that cut his business out because they wanted ice beer instead of new home beer.
What kind of business was your father in?
He was in the dry goods business.
Had that drag of the business for some time in 1895 or 6, I think.
I just had that recently, but.
He and his brother started the business in 1891.
But the brother went to Yoakum to open up a store.
And Lewis Halley, he kept the store in Victoria.
And he was there up until 1949 when he died of a heart attack.
Mother had the store then for three or four years.
then sold it to the brother.
He came back to Victoria.
At that time, he had sold his store before and he didn't have any occupation.
Uh-huh.
And then, so, you were born in Victoria.
I was born in Victoria.
And what was the date of your birth?
April the 10th, 1895.
Okay.
I'm not sure that I caught the age of your father at his death.
He was 49.
And he died when?
Oh, OK.
I seemed to think that you had said 1940 earlier.
Well, mother died.
Your mother died in 1940.
Well, I was married only two weeks before the father died.
Uh-huh.
What factors were involved in your choice of Texas A&M?
Why did you decide to go there?
Well, before they had some land, had some farmland, and I wanted to go there to learn how to farm.
I wasn't interested into being a businessman.
I wanted to go outdoors.
And where was this land?
It was in Victoria County.
Victoria County.
What procedures did you go through to enter Texas A&M?
Well, I didn't have any particular.
I entered it on a special permission from the president.
Had you finished Victoria High School?
No.
No.
I didn't finish any high school.
So you had to have special permission to enter at age 16?
Yeah.
And what were your reactions to the school when you first arrived?
Did you know enough about it to know what to expect?
No, I didn't know a thing about it.
You just knew that there was a Texas A&M and wanted to go there?
Texas A&M, yeah.
I don't think anybody ever said anything to me about it before.
Oh, I had a brother there that was there a year, a year ahead of me.
Yeah.
So you were...
He could have told you then a little bit about the problems the freshmen encountered when they got there.
Yeah, I guess he did tell me about it.
I was lucky, though.
I didn't get hazed too much.
I got one whip in one time with these triangle rulers.
It got a groove in it, you know, and they sting.
They sting, yeah.
I'm assuming you arrived there by train.
Did you arrive during the day or during the night?
Father took me up there, but I don't know how we got there.
Whether we had to go to Bryan, stop at a hotel there, and then come out on that trolley.
Probably did that, but I don't remember.
Okay.
Did you have any choice in the military company to which you were assigned the first year?
I don't think I was.
I think they just put me where they wanted me.
Where they had place, huh?
They put me in Company C when I first went up there and then I went to Company B and stayed in Company B I guess about three years.
And where were you housed in Company C?
Company C was housed in Foster.
So that was one of the older dormitories.
I presume you had the pleasure of holding wood and water for the upperclassmen?
Yeah, wood and water.
And the other one was in Goodwin Hall.
We had a little better accommodations there.
Yeah, that one was a fairly new one at that time, wasn't it?
Goodwin is now used as a classroom building.
It is?
Yeah.
I don't know exactly when it was converted to classroom, but quite a long while back, I believe.
Would you describe a typical day while you were there?
Sort of tell us what you did during a whole day, when you got up and what you did the first thing and when you went to class and what you did in the afternoon, if you can remember.
And when you went to bed?
No, I pretty well followed the schedule.
I don't know.
Do you remember what the schedule was?
I sure don't.
Can you tell us a little bit about life in the dormitories, particularly in Foster Hall?
What sort of things did you have to do?
Did I see Foster Hall?
Yeah, I believe so.
Yeah.
It wasn't Foster Hall.
There was another one down there.
Was it Prez Ross?
I had it on my mind a while ago, but I...
Well, in Goodwin Hall, we often would come into our room and find a push the door open and get hit with a pan or a bucket of water.
And that's about the only
The day I got there, of course, I wasn't a freshman then, but those pranks would go on anyhow.
You mentioned earlier that you had a brother who went there the year before you did.
Did he go back the second year?
Yeah, they had a two-year course at that time, and he finished his two-year course.
Yes, but I went on to finish the four-year course.
Did you by any chance room with him the first year you were there?
Yes, I roomed with him.
So you had a sophomore as your roommate the first year.
Was there a little bit of an advantage to having that?
I believe it was.
You had a little bit of protection.
However, he didn't get me out at one time.
I suppose it would have been a little bit of an advantage to have a sophomore older brother
on your side, at least part of the time.
Back to the dormitories, I believe the old ones were Foster, Ross, Austin, and Pfeiffer.
Pfeiffer's the one.
Pfeiffer's the one.
Okay.
Did they have inside showers and inside latrines?
No, when we were in Pfeiffer, we had to
go about two or three blocks to an auditorium down there with one separate building with showers.
And when you walked in there, that sulfur smell was awful.
Do they still have that up there now?
Well, they all have showers in all the dormitories, and I don't notice a sulfur smell to the water.
Well, when you used to walk in that place, there's an awful smell of sulfur.
Walk down there and take your shower, and then walk about a block or so back to your dorm.
What about a latrine?
Did you have those in the building, or were they in a separate building too?
Yeah, they were there.
I think they were in .
I don't remember when it was.
There was a time somewhere about the turn of the century where they had a brick out building, which they called the sink.
That was the only, well, maybe I shouldn't say the only toilet, but that's what it was.
It was a rather small brick building with a real tall chimney that they called the sink.
But in the new dormitory, Goodman, you had showers and toilets.
toilets on every floor, I think.
They had one tub, I think, on each floor, too.
One tub there.
What about the food in the mess hall?
I believe you had two different mess halls while you were there, didn't you?
The old one burned one year.
Yeah, the first one burned on the eleventh day of the eleventh month of the eleventh year.
So that would have been your first year there, wouldn't it?
Yeah, the first year I hadn't been there very long.
And I don't remember getting into that new one at all.
I guess I did in about 1915.
Yeah, I believe they had it in about 12 or 13, but you had a temporary.
Well, that one burned down, and then they built a temporary one after that.
out of galvanized iron.
And the night after a dance, White caught a fire and burned up.
And I think they sent us home for several weeks right around the Christmas time.
So we had to eat with the mess kits.
But that was the year of the fires, too.
There was more fires there in 11 and 12.
And any year that I know of, I believe they'd have.
They had that mess hall, I think the main building burned.
The main building burned in 12 sometime.
And then there's a tent, there's a tent row out there.
The tents caught a fire, and then the steam plant had a fire down there.
They must have had 10 or 12 fires in that one year.
All in that one between September and May.
Did you know any of the people who lived in the tents?
Yeah, boys that used to run around with, but I can't, I think one name was Colin, but he's been dead many years.
I imagine the life in the tent was a little bit different than that in the dormitory, wasn't it?
Oh, it must have been.
Particularly when it got cold.
Oh, yeah.
They had stoves in them, though, I believe, didn't they?
Well, they had some kind of a stove, but I don't remember.
Yeah, come rainy weather, too, there was no pavement there, and that ground would get wet, and it would be nasty.
What about the ground between the other buildings?
Was there any kind of walkways?
I'm sure you didn't have concrete sidewalks like we have today, but...
Did you have any gravel walks or anything like that to keep them getting in the mud so much?
I don't know just what they did.
Can you tell me about any privileges that the upperclassmen, that is the sophomores, juniors, and seniors, might have had that the freshmen didn't have?
What sort of things could they do that, as a freshman, you couldn't do?
I don't know as about that, but I did.
There's two trains come in there, the INGN and Southern Pacific.
Well, I could take one train and go to Navasota and see a girl.
and catch the other train and come back and get back by midnight.
So they probably had hours that you could stay out on.
But that would have been after your freshman year, I think, if you could do that.
What kind of things did you do for recreation or entertainment?
Well, I walked out quite a bit on the days off, took Kodak pictures.
Did you keep those Kodak pictures?
Yeah, I got them, but I can't find them.

I mean, did you take pictures of the campus or the... Well, there's a campus from the surrounding country and we would take long hikes and go to the little old store out there on, I don't know which direction it is, I'd get mixed up in the directions.
of there because east is west and so forth.
So I went out to the little old store and had a bunch of carnation, dime brand carnation milk and ginger crackers and almost got sick on eating that.
And there was a Bohemians had a hall just pretty close to the campus there and they used to have parties.
And we used to go over there, and the boys would bring home some of that sausage, you know, and stick it under the nose of some of the boys in the dormitory.
It was a strong-smelling sausage.
Uh-huh.
Was that some of the boys that didn't like the sausage?
They were kind of bedeviling with the smell, huh?
Yeah.
Did the student body or the Corps of Cadets, as they were when you were there, take a long hike down to the brasses for a night or two while you were there?
I don't think we did, but we used to go at night and go coon hunting.
go coon hunting.
They had a neighbor on there that had some dogs and he'd go coon hunting.
Uh-huh.
You mean just go off the campus someplace to go coon hunting?
Yeah, go coon hunting.
The Corps used to go to Dallas to the fair.
Then we'd take our uniforms and our guns and we'd do some parading there at the Dallas County Fair.
But that's the only time that I know that we went in a group.
Okay.
Did you have any favorite instructors?
Well, Thornton was an instructor, and he is the one that taught me into four years of finishing my course, four years.
And Bill Singh.
The entomology, I kind of liked him, and I was interested in entomology, although my major is supposed to be agronomy.
Yeah, this is, the Thornton, is that Duke Thornton?
I believe that's what they called him.
He was in chemistry?
I don't know what he was.
Or chemical engineering?
I guess he was.
He's still living?
Yes.
My assistant interviewed him a couple weeks ago in this same program.
The most distinguished professor there was old Botany Ball.
O.M.
Ball?
O.M.
Ball.
Did you have courses under him?
Yeah.
How about Dr. Francis in vet medicine?
Oh yeah, Dr. Francis, he was a
I always enjoyed going to his class because it turned out to be a show.
What sort of things did he do?
I don't know.
He'd say something that would get the class tickled.
He kept his class, I think, a pretty good mule.
What...
attitude or opinion did the students have toward the administration?
That would be both to the president and to the commandant.
I believe you had two different presidents while you were there, didn't you?
Yeah, I had Catfish... Milner?
Catfish Milner.
And Bissell, I think, wasn't it?
Yeah, Bissell.
Well...
It seemed to me like everything was going fine.
However, we did get out on a strike.
And I think there's some, they had company football teams.
And the boys on, I think it was Company D, got thrown off the team, several of them did.
I don't know why.
But there's 466 of us struck and went home.
Some of the boys, when they got home, why, their father sent them right back.
But my father let me stay home several weeks, and he finally said either go to school or go to work.
So we went back up.
When we got to college, we had to humiliate ourselves and sign a pledge not to strike.
I've heard a couple of people refer to Mr. Milner as Catfish Milner.
Do you have any idea where he got that nickname?
I believe it's the shape of his mouth.
I'm not sure.
I'm not sure, but I think it's the shape of his mouth.
What about Dr. Bazell?
Did the students have any... Now, back to the strike a minute.
Was that...
Strike, was Mr. Milner involved in that strike at all?
I don't think so.
I don't know what it brought about.
At that time, we were following the crowd.
Uh-huh.
But a whole bunch of you.
Yeah.
I don't know how many students were at that place at that time, but it seems to me something like about 750.
It may have been more than that.
But a whole bunch of you took off and went home.
Yeah, it was 400 and I think it's 466.
Mm-hmm.
And then some of them came right back, and some of them came back after a while.
Yeah, Father, Son, and back, and they finally drove back.
Probably some of them never did come back.
Mm-hmm.
I went back.
Did you have to make up for lost time when you came back?
I mean, you missed several weeks.
No, we didn't make it.
Of course, we had to pass our tests as they come.
So you didn't have to make up all the work that you missed.
No, I didn't have to put in any extra.
What about to the commandant?
Did you have any run-in with him?
Do you remember who the commandant was?
No, I never had any.
Never had any trouble in the military line at all.
Do you remember who the commandant was?
I don't know.
I got a yearbook there.
I probably would tell you.
Oh, OK. Well, I'm sorry.
I was just wondering if you remembered right offhand what his name was and if you had any thoughts about him.
We know that a lot of the students had some type of employment while they were at school.
Did you ever have a part-time job while you were there?
Well, the first money I ever really earned in my life was counting tags to go on feed bags.
But that didn't last long.
That was only for a few days.
You did that at school?
There was one fellow that used to come around with a bucket with candy and go around selling candy.
And I don't know of any other ones that
That worked at all.
There may have been some working in the mess hall.
But I don't know of anybody else.
Did the students who played football and basketball, well you didn't have basketball then, but football and baseball for the college team have any special privileges?
I don't know.
They have a separate table for them to eat at?
Let's see.
I did go through your senior yearbook, and there was an indication there that you belonged to a number of organizations.
And I'd like to ask you about those, if you remember what they were.
One of them was the Foundry Toter Club.
I don't know.
I belonged to a Newman Club there.
Yeah, that was, I believe, the Catholic Boys Club.
I don't know of any special thing we did.
We would have to go to Bryan to go to Mass on Sundays at that time.
Was the whole Corps of Cadets marched to the chapel for services on Sunday?
There was a period when I know that they were all marched to the chapel, or was in the assembly hall, sometimes called the assembly hall, and then the chapel.
I don't remember anything about that.
But anyway, the Catholic boys went to Bryan, to the church.
Went to Bryan.
There was an organization called the 466 Club.
Do you remember anything about that?
That's the strike.
Okay.
That's the strike bunch.
That's the strike, huh?
So it was what, 466 of you?
It was 466 of us.
Well, a strike.
What about the Veterans of the Lost Cause?
Well, that was an organization where you dress up in tacky clothes.
Mm-hmm.
And some ridiculous goes, I got a picture in there of me.
So you just did that on one day?
Yeah, I think it was just one day.
It only was.
I was wondering whether that might have had something to do with the strike, too, whether that was the fellows who came back.
No.
No, I think that was an annual event.
We were all privates, I think.
Well, let's see.
Would that have been junior privates?
Would that have been privates who were juniors?
According to the yearbook, you were veterans of the lost cause in 13 and 14, which would have been your junior year.
Well, I guess it belongs to those that have been privates all their lives.
There was no corporals, no sergeants, no officers, nothing.
That was the lost cause.
And then according to that, you stayed as a private all four years.
Yeah, I stayed a private all four years.
I gather you didn't...
I had the honor of being officer of the day several times, but I was still a private.
You were still a private.
And...
But, okay.
When you...
Graduated then in the spring of 1915.
Did you have a job lined up for you, or what did you do?
Well, the father had this farm, and I went on to it.
And so you did general farming there for a while, huh?
Yeah, started the farm.
What kind of crop did you raise?
mostly cotton at that time.
And for how long did you do that?
Well, I did that I guess there for about three years, and then he bought another farm.
I had two farms then, and I went to the second farm, which was a diversified farm.
It had cattle, timber, and
seven different grades of land.
Where was that, Luke?
It's in Victoria County, but it was about 15 miles apart.
Did you participate in the First World War at all?
First World War?
Yeah, I was in the First World War.
In what capacity?
I stayed as a special duty at Travis.
writing service records, data and service records.
Then after the war ended, they transferred me over to Kelly Field and I was in the Quartermaster at Kelly Field.
And so you say that was after the war ended?
Yeah.
And then you stayed in the Army for a little while then?
No, I was discharged on January 26, 19,
19, from the, from Kelly Field.
From Kelly Field, and where did you go after that?
Well, I married on March the 3rd, 1919, and I stayed on these, on these farms until we got
